<item>
            <title>[LUCENE-3619] in trunk if you switch up omitNorms while indexing, you get a corrumpt norms file</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/LUCENE-3619</link>
                <project id="12310110" key="LUCENE">Lucene - Core</project>
                        <description>&lt;p&gt;document 1 has &lt;br/&gt;
  body: norms=true&lt;br/&gt;
  title: norms=true&lt;br/&gt;
document 2 has &lt;br/&gt;
  body: norms=false&lt;br/&gt;
  title: norms=true&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;when seeing &apos;body&apos; for the first time, normswriterperfield gets &apos;initial fieldinfo&apos; and &lt;br/&gt;
saves it away, which says norms=true&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;however, at flush time we dont check, so we write the norms happily anyway.&lt;br/&gt;
then SegmentReader reads the norms later: it skips &quot;body&quot; since it omits norms&lt;br/&gt;
and if you ask for the norms of &apos;title&apos; it instead returns the bogus &quot;body&quot; norms.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;asserting that SegmentReader &quot;plans to&quot; read the whole .nrm file exposes the bug.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
